<TITLE> Police will be reformed to make it more modern: Sahara </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 30 (bdnews24.com)--Home minister Sahara Khatun has again promised to reform the police force to make it more modern and technology-dependent. "The prime minister has given the go-ahead to resolve all the problems facing the police to make it more modern," she said on Wednesdayat a citizen's rally after the launch of Bangshal Police Station in Dhaka. This is the 39th police station to be launched in Dhaka City Corporation area. Sahara pointed out that policeman, after overnight duty, do not get enough space to sleeping in the barracks and said more barracks will be built. They will also get access to better medical treatment and their children to education, she said. She promised better transports and arms for the law-enforcers and said greater numbers of policewomen will be sent to UN peacekeeping missions. State minister for home Shamsul Haque Tuku alleged that terrorism set off in the country after Police were mishandled following the killing of independence hero Sheikh Mujibur Rahman. Inspector general of police Nur Mohammad said, 'Police are the most-talked about and criticised agency of the government. But the responsibility does not end with criticism of police. "If it happens, then we have to get back to that criticised police." He asked people to file complaints with top police officials if the police do not provide them service.
